TY  - JOUR
T1  - Finite sample power of linear regression autocorrelation tests
AU  - Krämer, Walter
AU  - Zeisel, Helmut
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 43
IS  - 3
SP  - 363
EP  - 372
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/03/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(90)90125-D
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769090125D
AB  - We consider autocorrelation tests in the linear regression model which can be expressed as ratios of quadratic forms in the true disturbances. Given a particular such test (as e.g., the Durbin-Watson test and many others), we show that there exist design matrices such that the power of the test drops to zero as autocorrelation among the disturbances increases. We also show how to compute this limiting power for arbitrary design matrices.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - On the compatibility of nested logit models with utility maximization
AU  - Börsch-Supan, Axel
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 43
IS  - 3
SP  - 373
EP  - 388
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/03/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(90)90126-E
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769090126E
AB  - The paper examines the relationship between the nested multinomial logit (NMNL) model and rational consumer behavior. We show that the Daly-Zachary-McFadden (DZM) condition of the validity of stochastic utility maximization in NMNL models is unnecessarily strong and leads too often to rejection of NMNL models with large dissimilarity parameters. In many cases, the distribution of the stochastic utility components in the NMNL model can be modified in a way that preserves the NMNL choice probabilities on a subset of RI, where I is the number of alternatives in the choice set. On this subset, the DZM condition can be violated without violating the restrictions of stochastic utility maximization.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Three-stage least squares with different instruments for different equations
AU  - Schmidt, Peter
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 43
IS  - 3
SP  - 389
EP  - 394
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/03/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(90)90127-F
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769090127F
AB  - The standard treatments of 3SLS assume that the same instrument set is valid for every equation. When this is not so, a generalized method-of-moments estimator proposed by Amemiya is available. This paper compares Amemiya's estimator to three estimators based on fitted values of the endogenous variables. Two of these estimators are inconsistent when the instrument set varies across equations. The third estimator, based on fitted values for the dependent variable as well as the endogenous explanatory variables, is consistent but inefficient relative to the generalized method-of-moments estimator.
